{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_frenchbulldog_ver04/data/sn83045433/00280764139/1920121501/0656.xml":{"full_text":"t\nCOMMERCIA\nFINANCIAL\nSECTION TWO.\n1920 ESTIMATES\nADVANCE OVER\nLAST YEAR'S CROP\nt Few Losses Are Recorded\nAmong Less Important\nCommodities.\nYEAR'S AREA LESS\nDifference of Fiu. Million\nAeres Indicated in Official\nStatement.\nThe total value of all important\n<*rops raised this year in the United\nStates was I5.14S.51S.000, the crop\nestimate bureau of the Department\nof Agriculture announced yesterday\nin an official statement. This computation\nwas based on prices paid\nfarmers on December 1.\nThe area of all Important crops\nwas given as 351. 062.405 acres compared\nwith 356.162,122 acres in 1919.\nj The 1920 value of some of the\nimportant crops described by the\nbureau follow*:\nCorn. $2,189,721,000: winter wheat.\nIS66.T41.000; spring wheat. $273.4\n65.000; all wheat. $1.14\"D.206.000;\nwhite potatoes. 6500.974.000; sweet\npotatoes. $126,629,000; oats. $719.7&2.000:\nbarley. $142,931,000; rye.\nS8g.60t.000; rice. $63,837,000. cotton.\n$914,590^000: sugar beets. $99,396,ih*0;\napples. $271,984,000 and tob<\nto. 5/9^.001.000.\nProduction of the important crops\ngiven uj follows: Corn. 3.132.367.000\nbushels in 1920. and 2.859.509.00o\nin 1919; white potatoes.\n4^0.458.000 bushels in 1920. and 357 542.000\nin 1919; apple*. 240.646.000\nbushels in 1920. and 153.238.000 in\n1919; sugar beets. 8.545.000 tons in\n1920. and 6.421.478 tons in 1919;\noats. 1.524.055.000 bushels in 1920.\nand 1.231.754.000 in 1919; barley. 202.024.000\nbushels in 1920. and 161.345,0*0\nin 1919: rice. 53.710.000 bushels\nin 1920. and 42.790.000 bushels in\n1919; rye. 69.218.000 bushels in 1920.\nand 88.909.000 bushels in 1919; hay.\n108. 233.000 tons in 1920. and 109.152.000\ntons in 1919; tobacco. 1.50*.061.000\npounds in 1920. and 1.463.323\n000 in 1919; cotton. 12.987.000\nbal^s in 1920. and 11.421.000 in 1919\nTb* acreages of important crops\nwere:\nCrop. 1920. 1919.\nCorn t04.R0l.ow0 10o.072.000\n.\"W inter wheat 37.993.000 49.105.000\nJ .vng wheat 1?.419.000 22 203.0o0\nAll wheat 57.112.000 72.308.000\n\"Potatoes 3.929.000 3.981.000\nI Bftet 1.337.000 1.091.<00\nCotton 36.383.000 33.466.000\nTobacco 1.894.400 1.920.800\nTlav 73.1S1.000 T5.260.000\nOats 43.323.000 41.835.000\nParley 8.083.000 7.19K.OOO\nRye 5.043.000 7.103.000\nSugar beets 882.000 2692.455\nWASHINGTON PRODUCE.\nEggs?Nearby. 85c; Southern. 78a\n0? average receipts. 79c.\nRutter?Print, 71c; creamery, extra.\n68a69c.\nCheese?June-held. 31s32c; newmade.\n28a29c.\nPoultry Alive: Roosters. 20c;\nturkeys. 40a45c; spring chickens,28a\n30c; white Leghorns. 25c; hens. 27a\n28c; keats. 40a45c. Dressed fowls.\n28c: springers. 28a32c; turkeys. 45a\n48c: roosters. 23c.\nCalves and Lambs?Calves. 17c;\nlambs. 12c; prime. 10c.\nHogs?9a10c; boars. 4a.5c.\nRabbits?Top#. 50-60 each; No. 2\nand kits. 20c.\nPork?Dressed: Small. 15c; medium.\n13c; heavy, lOallc.\nSheep?3a 6c.\nGreen Fruits?Apples, per basket.\n75a2.00; apples, new. per bbl..\n$2.50*7.50; pineapples. $6.00a8.00;\nr California oranges. $10.00al2.00; California\nlemons, per box. $3.00a4.00;\ngrapefruit, per crate. $4.00a4.75;\nI Florida oranges. $4.00a5.00; Brussels\nsprouts, 10a 20c.\nVegetables?Potatoes, nearby, per\nbbl. $T00a3.25: Northern, per sack.\n3.25a3.50, string beans, per basket.\nFlorida. 3.O0a4.00; cabbage. per\nbbl.. $1 OOal.50; beets, per 100. $6.10a\n8.00; lettuce. North Carolina, per,\ncrate. $1.00al.25; romainc lettuce,\nper crate, fl.00a2.00; Florida. $2.50a\n3.00: peppers, per crate. $3 00a4.00;\ncymltngs. crate. $3.00a4 00; eggplant.\nper crate. $4 00a5 00; Onions,\np^r sack. $1.75a2.00; spinach, per\nbbl.. 2.50a3.00: Florida tomatoes.\nj,er crate, $2.00a7.00; sweet potatoes.\nNo. 1. per bbl.. $4.00a5.00:\ncelery. 50ca$1.00 per dor.: New York\ncelery, per crati. $4.00a6.00.\nHay. Grain. Flour, Feed?Furnished\nby U. S. Bureau bf Markets.\nBased on December 14 quotations in\nimportant markets prices for hay.\nfeed and trrain in markets delivered\nWashington. D. C., for prompt shipare\nquoted as follows: No. 1\ntimothy hay. 133 ton: No. 2 timothy\nhay, $30 ton; No. 1 clover mixed. $39\nt6n: spring wheat bran. $37 ton;\nspring wheat middlings. >34.30 ton;\ncottonseed meal (36 per cent) $37.25\nton: oM proces linseed meal. (47.50\nton: gluten feed. $55 ton; hominy\nfeed, $42 ton: dried beet pulp. $49\nton: No. 2 yellow corn. $1.03H bu.:\nNo. J white corn, $1.01 >j bu.; No. 2\nwhite oats. 61 He bu.: No. 3 white\ncats. $014c bu.\nThe following prices are quoted\nby local dealers on carlots, basis cash\npayment: No. 1 timothy (western)\nhay. $$5 ton; No. timothy (western)\nhay. $34 ton: No. 1 clover mixed.\n$32 ton: spring wheat bran. $3$ ton;\nwinter wheat bran. $41 ton. Flour:\nSoft winter straight (140 lbs. Jute).\nto $9 per bbl; hard winter\nstraight (140 lbs. Jute) $0 to\nper bbl.; fancy spring patent (family\nbrand) $8.25 to $*.25 per bbl.: No. 2\nshelled corn. S1.0C per bu. (bags extra);\nNo. white oats. C?s per bu.\n(bags extra).\nMonetary Conditions\nRemain Unchanged\nNEW YORK. Dee 14.?Monetary\nconditions were unchanged today.\nDemand and supply of call funds\nwere about even at 7 per cent, the\nrenewal flrure. The time money\nmarket was nominal again at ;%t\nper cent.\n4, Prime bank acceptances showed a\nfair, movement at unchange# quotations\nThe situation was unaltered\nla prime mercantile paper,\nwith a general minimum discount\nfigure of per cent and occasional\ntransactions slightly under that\nSports\nm j|c jj\nWASHINGT\nU. S.ANNUALLY PRODUCES\n2,500,000 TONS OF GYPSUM\nProduct Used Chiefly as Wall Plaster,\nBut Also Figures in Fertilizer.\nThe peculiar properties of plaiter of Paris have been known\nsince before the date of recorded history. The Egyptians used this\nsubstance more than 4,000 years ago, and it is said that some of the\nplaster work within the Pyramids is hard and durable today. Plaster\nof Paris is made from the common mineral known as gypsum. I41\ntechnical language gypsum is hydrous calcium sulphate, or in other\nwords, it is the sulphate of lime with its water of crystallization.\n1 Plaster of Paris, or calcined gypsum, is made by heating the crude\nI material to a temperature sufficient to drive off the water of crystalli1\nzation. It then forms a fine powder which, when water is added\" to\nj it, will agath become a hard,\"smooth, durable product.\nCrude gypsum is widely scattered throughout the world. In the\nUnited States it occurs chiefly as rock gypsum, or as gypsite, a soft\nearthy substance. It is also found in crystalline form as selenite_and\nsatin spar. The production in the United States has been relatively\nstationary for the last ten years. The average annual production is\naboi}t 2,500,000 tons of the crude mineral. In 1916 and 1917 production\nincreased slightly reaching a little over 2,750,000 tons in the\nformer year. In 1918 there was a drop in production to just oyer\n2,000,000 tons. This was caused chiefly by the cessation of building\noperations. In 1919 the estimated production is 2,430,000 tons. Before\nthe war 400,000 to 500,000 tons were imported each year, chiefly\nfrom Nova Scotia and New Brunswick. In recent years there\nhas been a big decrease in imports which reached a low point of\nless than to.qoo tons in 1918. and were less than 200,000 tons in 1919.\nNew York State ranks first in the production of gypsum. The annual\noutput there is between 500,000 and 600poo tons. Iowa and Michigan\nrank next with an annual output of from 300,000 to 400,000 tons each.\nOhio. Oklahoma and Texas are also important producing States.\nApproximately 500,000 tons of gypsum are consumed annually\nwithout calcining. The bulk of this material is used in connection with\nthe manufacture of Portland cement. The next largest use of raw\ngypsum is that of a fertilizer. For this purpose it is commonly known\nas land plaster. Its action here is indirect and not as a plant food\nitself. Its action is supposed to set free magnesia and potash which\nare valuable plant foody. Land plaster is also used in connection\nI with manure and stable litter. Its action here is to unite with the\nI ammonia of the manure to form ammonium sulphate. This latter\nis an easily available plant food and is not readily given off into the air\nnor washed away by rain. Raw gypsum is also used for making\nI common blackboard crayon, as a base for paints, as a filler for cotton\nand other minor purposes.\nBy far the most important use of calcined gypsum is tor wall\nplaster. About 1,500,000 tons arc consumcU annually for this purpose.\nMore recently gypsum has been used extensively for the\nmanufacture of plaster board, for tiles, blocks, roofing, etc. These\nare extensively used in the highest type of fireproof buildings All\ngypsum products are very poor conductors of heat and very resistant\nto fire.\nOther less important, but well known, uses of calcined gypsum\ni arc for making statuary and other art work, relief maps and models,\nI molds for pottery, surgical casts, asbestos pipe covering, etc.\nThe following table gives the production and imports of gypsum\nI as reported by the Geological Survey for recent years.\nPRODUCTION AND IMPORTS OF GYPSUM.\n(Short ^ons.)\nYear Production (crudo) Imports**\n1913- 2,599,508 453.776\nI9t4 2476465 373.780\n191 5 2447611 343.03191\n6 2.757.730 266437\n191 7 2,696,226 257,286\n191 8 2,057,015 56.881\n191 9 2430,000- 182,335\nF.stimated.\nIncludes unground, ground ;cnd Kcenes ccn>ent.\n(Copyright, 1920. by The Washington Herald.)\nWALL STREET GOSSIP. PHILADELPHIA PRODUCE.\nNEW YORK. Dec. 14.?Oil men PHILADELPHIA, Dec. 14.?Butwho\nat the close of last week said ter (Close)?IJigher.' The quotathat\nannouncement of \"favorable\" tions: Freih solid-packed creamery,\ndevelopments in Mexico would be fancy, high scoring. 56a58c; extras.\nma/. ,K? tUim S3c; extra firsts, 53a54c; firsts. 41a\nmade at the beginning of this week\n49c; seco