rise in Dutch Oulders.\nToday's market movements were\nnot accompanied by any special\nnews. Sentiment changed with the j\nchange in- the tone of the market I\nand the majority of those who went\nhome bearish last night were today\nexpressing the view that the decline\nhad been overdone. It is now predicted\nthat those who play for the\ncustomary \"secondary reaction\" will\nhave to pay the penalty for their\npessimism.\nAside from these superficial considerations.\nmore attention is b^lng\ngiven to the constructive results\nthat may be expected Lrom the new\norganization to finance our foreign\ntrade, as well as the efforts of the\nWar Finance Corporation now in\nstages of revival. Undoubtedly, the\ncommodity markets will furnish the j\ncue in this direction more accurately\nthan securities. The grain markets\nshowed continued strength through- j\nout the session, and cotton rallied\nabout $2 per bale, notwithstanding\nyesterday's bearish crop estimate.\nMoney conditions showed no\nchange, and the c^ll rate remained\nat 7 per cent. Sterling was somewhat\nfirmer around 3.45. wtth demand\ngood.\nWHEAT MARKET\nSHOWSSTRENGTH\nWire Trouble East of Chicago\nMakes Selling Light.\nHowever.\n^CHICAGO, Dec. 14.?The wheat)\nArket was strong all through the\nearly part of the session today, on\nlocal buying with a fair commission\nhouse demand, while offerings were j\nlight. In the last hour there was\nincreased selling, including consld-'\nI crable profit-taking by local bulls.\nwhile the sharp reaction in corn,\nchecked buying for a time. Wire\nsorvice was crippled east of Ch?ago\nand as a result the volume of trade\nwas smaller than usual and export j\ntrade reports were late in comlpg\\\nin\nIn the late trade there was also\nsome evening-up in anticipation of\nt the final government crop figures for i\nthe year. Resting prices ,were 2*4;\nto 3*4 cents higher, the May gain[\ning a little on December. Changing\ni operations were noj. as aggressive\nas they have been for several days j\npast.\nCorn finished j to 1U cents high-<\ner, oats gained H to cents, rye\nwas 1 U cents up and barley 2 cents!\nhigher. Corn showed a strong tone\nuntil the last hour when there was\nheavy selling against the offers, and\npressure from realizing by local j\nlongs, which dissipated a large part j\nof the early gains.\nNews affecting oats was of no\ngreat significance, but the upturns\nir. other markets caused a firmer\ntone. Gains were shaded by increased\nselling pressure in the late\ntrade, however, leaving the net advance\nfor the day small.\nKEEP CHECKI1\n#EARNING\nWith the up-to-dat\nTrust Company at y\nkeep your checking\nwork earning intere\ni other inactive or tun\nI 1 income.\nj This institution ii\nwhether small or larg\npmd M Chtckutg mmd\nUnionTrus\nOP THE DISTBK\nEDWARD J.STELI\nPage 3 of This S\nJ\n3DAY, DECEMBER\nt\nHome Again After\nFinancier's Dinner\n\n4 A\nCH.ULII J. BELL.\nPresident of the American Security\nti Trust Company, who was one\nof Washington's honored one? at\nthe dinner given in New York Monday\n\"evening In honor of Davies\nWarfleld. president of the Continental\nTrust Company of Baltimore.\nSALE OF COTTONS\nCLOSES STRONGER\nAdvances of 20 to 42 Points\nShown in Closing\nQuotations.\nNEW YORK. Dec. 14.?A shaip,\nrally occurred in the cotton market\ntoday and the close was strong- j\ner, following depression in the fore-\nnoon. December made a new low\nrecord for the season in the morn-\nIng, touching 14.66, compared with\n14.86. the low mark established to-i\nward the end of last month, while\nJanuary sold at 14.78. contrasted\nwith 14.53. the bottom point made!\nlate in November.\nThe market was fairly steady\nearly, with first prices 3 to 7 points j\nlower.\nDemand lacked breadth. and J\nprices soon began to sag under sell- j\nIng from Wall Street, commission j\nhouses and Southern sources. Late i\nin the forenoon the dccllne was\nchecked by covering, which becamc\nmore active as soon as the liquidation\nof scattered long accounts subsided\nThere also was buying or\nMatch and May by leading spot\nhouse brokers.\nThe undertone of the market was\nmuch better during the afternoon,\nalthough there were occasional reactions.\nA holiday at New Orleans\ndiverted the selling that might have\ngone to that market into New\nVork. Just before the close prices\nscored smart gains, based on active\ncovering by shorts and Liverpool\nand trade buying. Final quotations\nshowed net advances of 20 to 45\npoints.\nSpot here was quiet at an advance\nof 30 points at lS.SOc for\nmiddling. There were no sales.\nThe Census Bureau's report on\nthe consumption of cotton will be\nissued at 10 s. m. tomorrow.\nMETAL MARKET.\nNEW YORK. Dec. 14. The following\nprices were quoted at the\nNew York Metal Exchange todaj:\nBar silver, domestic. 99 >i Cents,\nunchanged; foreign. SIVi cents, a\ndecline of >4 cent.\nCopper, spot. December. January.\nFebruary, March, offered. 141ic;\nmarket dull.\nTin (Straits shipment). DecemberJanuary.\n33a35c; January-February.\n34>ia3iVkc; February-March. 35a3tc:\nmarket weak for nearby positions,\nand firmer for later.\nLead. spot. December and Januar.\noffered. $5.00; market dull.\nSpelter (East St. Louis), spot, December,\nJanuary. February and\nMarch, offered, *5.95; marktt weak.\nU. S. STEEL.\nThe buying in U. S. Steel today\nwas of the same character which\nhad been In progress for two weeks\nor more. It has been hinted that\nshorts selling Steel under 80 were\n\"selling into a bag.\" and the actio*\nof the stock today confirmed\nthe impression.\nCorner\n15 \"tb Mid H Sta.\nNortKwe?t jj\nNG BALANCES\nINTEREST I\ne service of the Union I\nour (fitpoitl you can I\naccount balances at I\njust a* you keep I\n>lus fund* earning an I\nrotM your Account I\n'*t C \\->A- -|_\nt St aa i p\nst Company\n:t or Columbia\n,WA<H?N, President J\nMl *1\nection\nteMd\nf\n15, 1920.\nMEN AND\nBr HICHAM\nRoger W. Babson. who has national\nif not international prominence\nas a statistician, will have a\nlively time filling his engagements\nhere Friday. At 10 a. m.,' Id the auditorium\nof the Chauffer of Commerce,\nhe is to meet his local cjlents.\nHe will speak on business\nconditions, and probably answer\nquestions put to him from the floor.\nAt 12:30 he will address a combined\nmeeting of the Building\nTrades Employers' Association, the\nCity Club, the Association of Credit\nMen and the ,?aies Managers' Association\nof Philadelphia at a luncheon\nin the Bellevue-Stratford.\nGeorge W. Norris, governor of the\nFederal Reserve Bank, will preside.\nMr. Babson's subject will be \"The\nBusiness Outlook for 1921.\"\nIn the evening, at the Metropolitan\nOpera House, he will address\nthe employes of his clients. His\nsubject will be \"How to Make Good\nin Business.\"\nIf the bill introduced by Senator\nSantos, in the territorial Senate\nManila, making it obligatory for\nFilipinos to wear \"pants\" becomes\nlaw the clothing manufacturer* of\nthe United States, now rather dejected.\nwould seem to have reason\nto put up.\nThe population of the Philippines\nis nearly 10.000,000.\nFenator Santos says the half-naked\ncondition of the pagans of the\narchipelago is used as an argument\nagainst the rapacity of the Filipino\nfor self-government. He proposes\nthat the government buy the\n\"pants\" and distribute them \"free,\ngratis, for nothing.\"\nSomebo<fy may confound Senator\nSantos by pointing to the fact that\none of tl\\e things the American\nwoman did immediately after being\nmade a citizen was to reduce radically\nthe amount of clothing with\nwhich she appeared in public.\nHowever, that does ndt concern\nmanufacturers of \"pantV\" The big\nthing to them is that there is prospe.\nt of large orders from the Philippines.\nThey are to be congratulated\ntoo. in not knowing that the\nterm \"pants\" gives a severe pain\nto worshipers at the shrine of\nLindley Murray.\nNow Harahan. of the C. O.\ncomes into the limelight. He was\na locomotive engineer on that road\nthirty years ago. Now he is president.\nWho says there is not room\nat the top\"\nGo over the list of railroad presTdents.\nCarl Gray, overlord of the\nUnion Pacific, was a telegrapher at\na way station in Arkansas Fred\nUnderwood, president of the Erie.\nBig Fiwe Packers\nSecure Postponement\nHearing in the case of the government\nagainst the \"Big 5\" packers\nwas postponed yesterday in the\nSupreme Court of the District of\nColumbia until Tuesday, Decembei\n21, when the matter of the separation\nof the corporations from\ntheir stockyard and terminal properties\nwill be again taken up. The\np&ckers asked for the postponement\nin order to examine further\nInto the government's proposal for\na trustee to take charge- of th?\nproperties, pending their disposal\nto private parties. It was the tacit\nunderstanding that the postponement\nwould be the last one asked\nand that the matter would be settled\nAnally next week.\nBALTIMORE PRODUCE.\n_\nBALTIMORE. Dec. 14. Eggs\nJVestern Maryland Pennsylvania\nand nearby, firsts. TSaSOc; Eastern\nShore Maryland and Virginia, firsts,\n78a80c; Western (Ohio), firsts. 78a\n?0c; West Virginia, firsts. 74c;\nSouthern (North Carolina), firsts,\n72c.\nLive Poultry?Chickens, young, by\nboat, per pound. I\"?a26c: do. scraggy.\npoor, per pound. 22c; old roosters.\npound. 18c; old hens, over 4\npounds, pound. 25c. do. small, pound.\n22c: white Leghorn hens, pound. 23\na24c; young white Leghorns. 1H\npounds. 23a24?.\nButter?Creamery. Western separator,\nextras, do. firsts. 53a\n54c; Western prints. \\z-pound, ex=E=\nI\nU rRARLEI C. CLOTE1\nf President.\nMILTOX E. AILES,\nVice Preside? t.\nWILLIAM J. FLATHB\nVlee Preslde?t.\nA JO>Hl A EVA*S. Jr.\nVice Pmidrat.\nI\nI From the middle s\nsuccess. The tide turns\ngance waking to pull\nHow much should we\nbeyond the ropes and i\nSaving i? a pleasure; a\n(Die?\nOn Renr&ytv\nCapital aa? Hrfls?,\nSjSBSBgS\nQUALIT\n.REALTY\nJ*\nBUSINESS 1\nSfltLAHE.\nr ;.r i.\nw\" brakeman. and A. J. Erfrling\nof the St. Paul, vu a telegrapher\nC. H. Markham president of the\nIllinois Central. a section laborer\n.on the Atchison. Topeka and\nSanta Fe. Samuel Rea. president\nof the Pennsylvania, began at\nwith a job fu the engineering department\nof the Pennsy. Howard\nElliotr, head of the New Haven and\nNorthern Pacific, was a rodman on\nthe Q,. B. Q. forty years ago A\nJ. Smith, president of the New York\nCentral\", was office boy on the Lake\nShore. The list might be continued\nuntil it embraced nearly every railroad\nchief in the country.\nWilliam J. Harahan went through\nthe proper school to fit him for running\na great property like the\nCheaapeake and Ohio. That school\nis the one of hard knocks and broad\nexperience. _\nIt will be Interesting if not vatuable\nto learn the effect of the advertising\nthe Fairbanks Company\nhas under way. No doubt' you noticed\nit in the main sheet of this\npaper. Usually an advertised advertises\nonly his goods The Fairbanks\npeople are going further.\nThey are advertiaing not only the\ngoods but the men back of the\ngoods.\nIn the series now appearing the\ncompany first pictured its Philadelphia\noffice building, at Seventh and\nArch streets. There was an at|\ntractive line cut of the exterior and\ni a bit of a story of what you would\nfind within.\nNext came an ad with a line cut\nI of the information desk and the\nman who presides there?Walter\n1 McDonald. The printed matter told\ni enough about him to Interest you\nand the picture made you remember\nhim as the courteous person you\nmet when you went to Fairbanks'\nj office.\nThen came an ad in which J. 8\nPierson. the manager, was featured.\nFollowing that was one showing\nE. P. Miller, manager of the Mill.\nMine and Railway Supply Departj\nment.\nSo it goes, through department\nafter department. The Fairbanks\npeople apparently not only want you\nto know the machinery and the\ntools they sell but the men who sell\nthem. That makes for something\nI mogt personal than there has been\nj in most branches of advertising,\nj surely in the business of concerns\nj like the Fairbanks Company. It has\ni the virtue not only of novelty, but\nof promoting the personal interest\nof the employes, for they are featured\nas being real elements in the\ni success of the business, which, of\ncourse, they are. but which has\nnot been recognized heretofore so\nfar as advertising was concerned.\ntras. 57a38c do, firsts. 55a?6c: West-\nem prints. 1-pound, extras. S?a66c;\n('do. firsts. auaStc; nearby creamery,\nextras. oOaDlc; do. firsts. 47a4&c:\ndairy prints, extras. 30aS?c; do.1\nfirsts. ?9a30c: Maryland. Pennsylvania\nand Virginia, store packed,\nfirsts. 23a?4c; rolls. West Virginia.\nextras, 30a31c.\nNon-Speculativ\nIn times such as the present\ndent investors turn naturally\nsafety to First Mortgage secur\non the land and its improvenu\nNo other kind of an invest?\nhas a better record for safety,\nbility and good yield.\nIf you have $250 or more for\nvestment, let us send our list\nselect First Mortgages on impr<\nWashington property, of conse\ntive valuation, tor considers!\nThere'll be no obligation.\nALLAN E. WALl\nReal instate aad\n813 15tk Street N. W.\n\nTHE TIDE IS GOING OUT.\nm there is no time to spare if we\ni and begins to go out. Tliere is 1\nis down. We've got to work, hori\nsave? Ten per cent is small enov\nin danger.*\nduty; it is easy. Open an account\n[ggsMma\nOF WASHINGTON DC\nonto Avenue feeing he UL 5\nfcvr Ik* Aatritaa lUakrr.' Ammmrtm\n>1\nH.m. ItfMirm, Cl*ar 1 Sultna 1\nI\nm, i\nm\n\nr\n\nf WANT ADS\nii BUDDING\n\nSECTION TWO.\nfOTORICOAL 1!\nMEN LOOKING TO I\nBRIGHT FUTURE\nAssert Non-activity SpefJ\nWill Soon Be\nBroken.\n???______ 2\nPLENTY IN EUROPE\n\nOverstocked Condition Exists\nAccount of Recent Pan\nicky Purchasing.\n4\nNEW YORK. Dec. 14.?While U%f*\nis. no demand for export coal and\nthat branch of the trade faces a\nserious situation, local coal men pre*,\nfess to see a raj of sunshine breaks\ning through *the clouds of noa-a^\ntiTity. acc